Documentation of the data sets:

a. The Baltimore City Employee Salary (2011-2021) test data set used for this project is publicly available by the city administration.

b. The dataset link : https://data.baltimorecity.gov/datasets/baltimore::baltimore-city-employee-salaries-2/about

c. The dataset includes Baltimore City employee salaries and gross pay from fiscal year 2011 through last fiscal year and includes employees who were employed on June 30 of the last fiscal year. For fiscal years 2020 and prior, data are extracted from the ADP payroll system. For fiscal year 2021, the data are combined from the ADP system and the Workday enterprise resource planning system which now includes payroll.


Documentation of any changes made to the original data sets

Manipulation of data can be found in the comment string of R CODE under ‘## Manipulating Data ##’ comment.

While exploring ‘## Manipulating Data ##’, you will find how we cleaned the data and used some of continuous variables into categorical and further grouped them for better insights of dataset.

The team’s opinion on the questions asked:

QUESTION 1. In what ways do you think data visualization is important to understanding a data set?

a. Data visualization is crucial in assisting the audience in better understanding the dataset by providing numerous visuals of the data with accurate trends and predictions.

b. A clear perspective is acquired about the importance of relations and trends in the dataset by mapping data to the appropriate business context.

c. It also aids in the time management of the concerned entity since examining the data visuals can help the audience obtain an understanding of the dataset in a comparatively shorter period of time.


QUESTION 2. In what ways do you think data visualization is important to communicating important aspects of a data set?

Data visualization is crucial in understanding any dataset as it provides with

a. Insights of current data

b. Relations in the dataset

c. Trends

d. Background of data and its observations

Gaining such aspects will further help the decision-makers and concerned entities with predicting future trends and improving business decisions/outcomes.


QUESTION 3. What role does your integrity as an analyst play when creating a data visualization for communicating results to others?

Data visualizations provided by us (Data Analysts) to the audience should depict true integrity ensuring that the data processed is in line with the original dataset and should provide meaningful and relative information and trends.


QUESTION 4. How many variables do you think you can successfully represent in a visualization? What happens when you exceed this number?

Visualization of a dataset to represent any information is usually processed with multiple variables (i.e, data visualization is multivariate). To depict data in a visual form in a meaningful manner, generally, a maximum of 4 variables can be used. If we exceed this number during visualization, it may lead to a chaotic representation with too many data points to differentiate between and will lead to an unclear image of what exactly the data is depicting.


Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

######Manipulating Data######
options(scipen = 999)
#bal_cit_data
ncol(bal_cit_data)
## [1] 11
nrow(bal_cit_data)
## [1] 154187
bal_cit_data_frame <-data.frame(bal_cit_data)

#Cleaning data
bal_cit_data_frame_new<-bal_cit_data_frame[is.na(as.numeric(bal_cit_data_frame$middleInitial)),]
bal_cit_data_frame_final <- bal_cit_data_frame_new[!is.na(bal_cit_data_frame_new$hireDate),]
bal_cit_data_frame_final$hireDate<-as.Date(bal_cit_data_frame_final$hireDate)
bal_cit_data_frame_final$hire_year <- format(bal_cit_data_frame_final$hireDate,format= "%Y")
bal_cit_data_frame_final$hire_year <- as.numeric(format(bal_cit_data_frame_final$hireDate,format= "%Y"))

#changing HireDate into categorical variable : Hire range
breaks <- c(1900,1970,1981,1992,2003,2014,2025)
bal_cit_data_frame_final$bin_range <- cut(bal_cit_data_frame_final$hire_year,breaks,labels=c("1900-1969","1970-1980","1981-1991","1992-2002","2003-2013","2014-2024"),include.lowest = TRUE)

#Removing 'FY' from the Fiscal Year data
bal_cit_data_frame_final$fiscalYear <- as.factor(gsub("FY","",bal_cit_data_frame_final$fiscalYear))

#Generating Annual Salary categorical variable
annual_break <- c(0,35000,70000,105000,140000,280000)
bal_cit_data_frame_final$annual_range <- cut(bal_cit_data_frame_final$annualSalary,annual_break,labels=c("Very Low","Low","Medium","High","Very High"),include.lowest = TRUE)

#Generating Gross Salary categorical variable
bal_cit_data_frame_final$grossPay <-round(bal_cit_data_frame_final$grossPay, digits = 0)
gross_breaks <- c(0,35000,70000,105000,140000,373111)
bal_cit_data_frame_final$gross_range <- cut(bal_cit_data_frame_final$grossPay,gross_breaks,labels=c("verylow","low","medium","High","very High"),include.lowest = TRUE)

#Generating Sectors/categories from Agencies
defence  <- c('A99','A64','A38','A54','A11','BPD','A08','A51','A26','A57','R01','D01')
public_works <- c('A50','A90','A04','A06','A49','B70','A67','C90','A70','A41','B49','A84','A68','B68','P04')
govt <- c('A03','A29','A31','A75','A40','A09','A30','A10','A01','A91','A02','A37','A33','A52','W07','A73','A35','A28','A86')
others <- c('A85','A83','A19','A46','A39','W08','W03','SCS','A51','A44','P83','U01','A65','P65')
finance <- c('A24','A17','A32','A15','A14','A23','A18','A16','A12','A88','A53')

bal_cit_data_frame_final$sector <- 
  as.factor(ifelse(bal_cit_data_frame_final$agencyID %in% defence, 'defence',
                     ifelse(bal_cit_data_frame_final$agencyID %in% public_works, 'public_works',
                     ifelse(bal_cit_data_frame_final$agencyID %in% govt, 'govt',
                     ifelse(bal_cit_data_frame_final$agencyID %in% others, 'others','finance')))))

#Creating additional data frame by excluding Hire_year : 1900(Outlier)
bal_cit_data_frame_filter <- filter(bal_cit_data_frame_final, hire_year != 1900)
#Creating theme for reusing it in graphs
mynamestheme <- theme(
  plot.title = element_text(family = "serif", face = "bold", size = (20),colour = "blue4"),
  legend.title = element_text(colour = "blue", face = "bold", family = "serif",size = (15)),

  axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = (15), colour = "blue4"),
  axis.text = element_text(family = "mono", colour = "blue1", size = (14)),
  legend.box.background = element_rect(fill='grey50'),
  plot.background = element_rect(fill='transparent', color='grey50'),
  plot.caption = element_text(family = "serif", size = (13), colour = "black")
)
#Two plots with single CONTINUOUS variable
ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x= grossPay,fill = 'red'),bins = 15) + scale_fill_brewer(type = "diverging", palette = 'Dark2') + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Salary distribution of Baltimore City employees") + labs(y= "Count of Employees", x = "Gross Pay", caption = "Majority of the workforce have a Gross Pay of approximately $50,000") + scale_x_continuous(labels =comma_format(decimal.mark = ","),scales::dollar_format()) + scale_y_continuous(labels=comma_format(decimal.mark = ",")) + theme(legend.position = "none") + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 300000), label = function(x) paste0("$", x))

##Two plots with single CATEGORICAL variable

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x= bin_range,fill = 'red')) + mynamestheme  + scale_fill_brewer(type = "diverging", palette = "RdYlBu") + ggtitle("Number of employees hired between the year 1900 and 2024") + labs(y= "Count of Employees", x = "Hiring Year range", caption = "Maximum employees were hired between the year 2003 and 2013") + scale_y_continuous(labels =comma_format(decimal.mark = ",")) + theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final,aes(x="",y=sector,fill=sector)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_polar("y") + labs(x="", y="") + theme(legend.position="bottom") + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Employee distribution across Sectors") + labs(caption = "Maximum employees belong to Defence Agency") + theme(panel.background = element_blank(), legend.title = element_blank(),axis.text.x=element_blank(),axis.ticks.x=element_blank(),axis.text.y=element_blank(),axis.ticks.y=element_blank(),plot.background = element_rect(fill='transparent', color='white')) 

#One plot between CATEGORICAL and CONTINUOUS variable

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) + geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x=annual_range, y = hireDate, color = sector)) + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Annual salary of employees hired between 1900 and 2020") + labs(y= "HireDate", x = "Annual Salary range", caption = "Majority of employees fall in the very low income range") + scale_color_discrete(name="Agency Division")

#Two plots showing relationship between two variables

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) +geom_point(mapping = aes(x = fiscalYear, y = grossPay, alpha = 0.3))+ geom_violin(mapping = aes(x = fiscalYear, y = grossPay, fill = fiscalYear)) + scale_fill_brewer(type = "diverging", palette = "RdYlBu") + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Gross salary of employees across Fiscal Years 2011 - 2021") + labs(y= "Gross Pay", x = "Fiscal Year", caption = "Gross salary of some employees is highest compared to others in 2020 fiscal year") + scale_alpha(guide = 'none') + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) paste0("$", comma(y)))

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) + geom_jitter(mapping = aes(x = bin_range,y =annualSalary,alpha = 0.1, color = "tomato")) + geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x=bin_range,y =annualSalary, alpha = 0)) + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Annual salary of employees hired between 1900 and 2024") + labs(y= "Annual Salary", x = "Hiring Year range", caption = "Annual salary of some employees is high compared to others during the year 2014 to 2024") + scale_alpha(guide = 'none') + guides(colour = "none") + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) paste0("$", comma(y)))

#one plot should use faceting and display information about four variables
ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_final) + geom_bar(aes(x=annual_range, fill = sector)) + facet_wrap(facets = vars(fiscalYear)) + ggtitle("Annual salary of employees covering all the agencies for each Fiscal year ") + labs(y= "Count of Employees", x = "Annual Salary range", caption = "Employees from govt and defense agencies fall under very high salary bracket in the Fiscal years 2016 to 2021") + scale_fill_discrete(name="Agency Division") + theme(
  plot.title = element_text(family = "serif", face = "bold", size = (17),colour = "blue4"),
  legend.title = element_text(colour = "blue", face = "bold", family = "serif",size = (15)),
  legend.text = element_text(face = "italic", colour = "blue4", family = "serif",size = (12)),
  axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = (10), colour = "blue4"),
  axis.text = element_text(family = "mono", colour = "blue1", size = (9)),
  legend.box.background = element_rect(fill='grey50'),
  plot.background = element_rect(fill='transparent', color='grey50'),
  plot.caption = element_text(family = "serif", size = (10), colour = "black"),
  axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)
)

#Competition Plot to win CHEESY price

ggplot(bal_cit_data_frame_filter) + geom_bar(aes(x = hire_year, fill = sector)) + transition_time(as.numeric(fiscalYear)) + geom_text(aes(x = min(hire_year),y = min(ObjectId), label = fiscalYear) , hjust='left', vjust = 'bottom', alpha = 0.2, col = "gray50", size = 20) + transition_states((fiscalYear), state_length = 4) + view_follow() + coord_flip() + mynamestheme + ggtitle("Variation in Hiring over Fiscal years across different Agencies") + labs(y= "Hire Year", x = "Employee Count", caption = "Highest number of Employees have been hired in defense sector over the years") + scale_fill_discrete(name="Agency Division") + theme(plot.title = element_text(family = "serif", face = "bold", size = (14),colour = "blue4"),plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0))
